x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">That=E2=80=99s sill=
y, of course. A based-on-true-events docudrama about the most public of pub=
lic figures would almost certainly withstand a libel claim=E2=80=94to say n=
othing of a request for a prior restraint on political speech. And the film=
=E2=80=99s most controversial scene=E2=80=94Trump raping then-wife <b>Ivana=
</b>=E2=80=94is based on her deposition testimony in their divorce, which s=
he later disavowed. At this point, we know Trump=E2=80=99s threats and laws=
uits never actually go anywhere; it=E2=80=99s all for show, to perpetuate a=
n image of strength and aggression. <br/><br/>In fact, the only result so f=
ar has been a bunch of additional free press for the movie, giving the film=
makers a chance to note that the film is actually a pretty sympathetic port=
rait of the man who would become president and co-star in <i>Home Alone 2: =
Lost in New York</i>. =E2=80=9CThe movie is <i>not</i> a hit
piece,=E2=80=9D screenwriter <b>Gabriel Sherman</b>, who=E2=80=99s also a w=
ell-known journalist, emailed me today. If you like Trump, he insists, you =
might actually like <i>The Apprentice</i>.  <br/> <br/>And yet here we are,=
 10 days after the premiere to worldwide attention, generally very good rev=
iews (78 percent fresh), and even some Oscar buzz for Strong and Stan, and =
<i>The Apprentice</i> hasn=E2=80=99t found a U.S. distributor. This despite=
 CAA and WME <i>both</i> hustling for buyers. The $15 million film sold pre=
tty easily in much of the world, minus China, Japan, India, and smaller ter=
ritories like Turkey. (Producers quietly presold many of the rights two yea=
rs ago at Cannes.) But there=E2=80=99s still no distributor in the U.S., wh=
ere its release would almost certainly generate tons of earned media and cu=
riosity, and contribute to the national dialogue about whether we should re=
elect Trump. So what, exactly, is going on here?<br/></td>
