x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">There are general b=
usiness reasons, of course, why <i>The Apprentice</i> hasn=E2=80=99t sold y=
et. Festival titles often take longer to find deals these days, both becaus=
e it=E2=80=99s a buyer=E2=80=99s market and because acquisitions are genera=
lly more complex. Plus, the ultimate decision-makers=E2=80=94especially on =
hot-button films that might lead the former and possible future president t=
o personally target the company=E2=80=94often aren=E2=80=99t on the front l=
ines at the festivals, requiring screenings back in L.A. or New York before=
 a distributor can pull the trigger. That=E2=80=99s happening now, and seve=
ral potential distributors haven=E2=80=99t fully screened the film yet. And=
 while Trump=E2=80=99s legal threats might be dubious, potential buyers wil=
l still take time to do their own legal review, just to be 100 percent comf=
ortable if and when Trump actually sues.     <br/> <br/>But I=E2=80=99ve
spent this week talking to many of those potential buyers, and several that=
 really liked the film are still out on <i>The Apprentice,</i> in part beca=
use of the politics of the moment=E2=80=94which is to say <i>fear</i> of th=
e politics of the moment. In short, this one movie isn=E2=80=99t worth beco=
ming a lightning rod, getting Bud Light-ed, finding the entire company in t=
he MAGA crosshairs. Those 12 jurors in New York were willing to stand up to=
 Trump today, but most modern entertainment executives aren=E2=80=99t nearl=
y as brave. <br/><br/>None would say so on the record, but the three major =
U.S.-based streaming services=E2=80=94all of which, remember, spend tens of=
 millions of dollars a year courting Oscar nominations=E2=80=94are, at leas=
t right now, declining to engage seriously on the movie. Apple, which found=
 <b>Jon Stewart </b>too hot to handle, is an obvious no. Amazon officially =
passed. Netflix=E2=80=99s awards team left Cannes last year with the <b>Jul=
ianne Moore</b>-<b>Natalie Portman</b> showcase
<i>May December</i> expressly to run an Oscar campaign for them (it didn=E2=
=80=99t work, but the film scored a screenplay nom). But Netflix is not bid=
ding on <i>The Apprentice</i>, I=E2=80=99m told. Disney=E2=80=99s Searchlig=
ht specialty division, Universal=E2=80=99s Focus label, A24=E2=80=94all pot=
ential buyers, and all not bidding. Lionsgate, which hasn=E2=80=99t had a r=
eal Oscar contender since <i>La La Land</i>, is not currently bidding, and =
that likely won=E2=80=99t change. Neither is HBO, which I thought might bit=
e on this because it=E2=80=99s in the vein of its political docudramas like=
 <i>Game Change</i>. <br/></td>
